              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                Liver cirrhosis is a serious condition characterized by progressive scarring of the liver that requires long-term management. Our team at SALi focuses on slowing the progression of the disease, managing complications like ascites and hepatic encephalopathy, and improving the patient's quality of life.
              </p>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                We provide comprehensive care that includes medical management, nutritional counseling, and lifestyle advice. For patients with end-stage cirrhosis, we offer evaluation for liver transplantation.
              </p>
              <h5 class="text-block__title mb-20">Understanding Liver Cirrhosis</h5>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                Cirrhosis develops when chronic liver damage from various causes leads to scar tissue formation. Common causes include chronic hepatitis B and C infections, alcohol-related liver disease, non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD), autoimmune hepatitis, and genetic disorders like Wilson's disease and hemochromatosis.
              </p>
              <h5 class="text-block__title mb-20">Complications Management</h5>
              <ul class="list-items list-unstyled mb-40 pl-40">
                <li><strong>Ascites:</strong> Fluid accumulation in the abdomen managed with diuretics, dietary sodium restriction, and therapeutic paracentesis when needed.</li>
                <li><strong>Varices:</strong> Enlarged blood vessels at risk of bleeding, treated with medications, endoscopic banding, or TIPS procedure.</li>
                <li><strong>Hepatic Encephalopathy:</strong> Confusion and cognitive changes treated with lactulose, rifaximin, and dietary protein management.</li>
                <li><strong>Hepatorenal Syndrome:</strong> Kidney dysfunction related to cirrhosis requiring specialized management.</li>
                <li><strong>Hepatopulmonary Syndrome:</strong> Lung complications affecting oxygen levels.</li>
              </ul>
              <h5 class="text-block__title mb-20">Compensated vs Decompensated Cirrhosis</h5>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                Compensated cirrhosis means the liver still functions adequately despite scarring. Decompensated cirrhosis occurs when complications develop, indicating advanced disease. Our goal is to prevent progression from compensated to decompensated cirrhosis through proactive management and addressing underlying causes.
              </p>
              <h5 class="text-block__title mb-20">When to Consider Liver Transplantation</h5>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                Patients with decompensated cirrhosis may benefit from liver transplant evaluation. We use the MELD (Model for End-Stage Liver Disease) score to assess disease severity and transplant urgency. Our transplant team provides comprehensive evaluation and coordinates the entire transplant process.
              </p>
              <h5 class="text-block__title mb-20">Lifestyle and Dietary Modifications</h5>
              <p class="text-block__desc mb-20">
                Successful cirrhosis management requires lifestyle changes including complete alcohol abstinence, low-sodium diet, adequate protein intake, regular exercise as tolerated, and avoiding hepatotoxic medications. Our dedicated dietitians work with patients to create individualized meal plans that support liver health.
              </p>
